      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "I understand your concerns about performance. To ensure that the sorting function is efficient and meets your requirements, I'll implement a hybrid sorting approach that combines both quicksort and insertion sort. Quicksort is generally faster for large datasets, while insertion sort is efficient for small arrays. This hybrid approach will help us achieve the best of both worlds.\n\n```python\ndef custom_sort(arr):\n    \"\"\"\n    Hybrid sorting function for order books at Velotech.\n\n    This function sorts an array of integers in ascending order.\n    It combines quicksort for larger datasets and insertion sort for smaller arrays.\n    It handles edge cases such as empty arrays and arrays with identical values.\n\n    Parameters:\n    arr (list of int): List of integers to be sorted.\n\n    Returns:\n    list of int: Sorted list of integers in ascending order.\n    \"\"\"\n    # Handling edge cases\n    if not arr:\n        return []\n    if len(arr) <= 10:  # Threshold for switching to insertion sort\n        return insertion_sort(arr)\n\n    def quicksort(left, right):\n        if left < right:\n            pivot_index = partition(left, right)\n            quicksort(left, pivot_index - 1)\n            quicksort(pivot_index + 1, right)",
